    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Climate Pact Without America</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Hugh G Cunningham letter holds calling Bush administration 'short-sighted' for refusing to join Kyoto participants because of 'potential drag on future American economic growth' (July 23 editorial) ignores present state of United States and world economies</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Calling the Bush administration ''shortsighted'' for refusing to join the Kyoto participants because of ''the potential drag on future American economic growth'' (editorial, July 23) ignores the present state of the United States and world economies.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Calling the Bush administration ''shortsighted'' for refusing to join the Kyoto participants because of ''the potential drag on future American economic growth'' (editorial, July 23) ignores the present state of the United States and world economies.</p>
        <p>Further, if Gerhard Schröder, the German chancellor, is, as you say, ''frustrated by Mr. Bush's unreasonable withdrawal from the Kyoto agreement,'' imagine Mr. Schröder's distress as he tries to improve the German economy while complying with the Kyoto treaty.</p>
        <p>HUGH G. CUNNINGHAM  Vero Beach, Fla., July 23, 2001</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
